### Arithmetic Operators

```dart
void main() {
  int a = 10;
  int b = 3;

  print(a + b);  // 13 (Addition)
  print(a - b);  // 7  (Subtraction)
  print(a * b);  // 30 (Multiplication)
  print(a / b);  // 3.333... (Division, returns double)
  print(a ~/ b); // 3  (Integer division)
  print(a % b);  // 1  (Modulus)
}
```

### Comparison Operators

| Operator | Meaning |
|----------|---------|
| `==` | Equal to |
| `!=` | Not equal to |
| `>` | Greater than |
| `<` | Less than |
| `>=` | Greater than or equal to |
| `<=` | Less than or equal to |

### Logical Operators

```dart
void main() {
  bool t = true;
  bool f = false;

  print(t && f); // false (AND)
  print(t || f); // true  (OR)
  print(!t);     // false (NOT)
}
```

### Assignment Operators

```dart
void main() {
  int x = 5;
  x += 3;  // x = 8
  x -= 2;  // x = 6
  x *= 2;  // x = 12
  x ~/= 3; // x = 4 (integer division assignment)
}
```

### Null-aware Operators

```dart
void main() {
  String? nullableString;

  // ??= assigns only if null
  nullableString ??= 'default';
  print(nullableString); // 'default'

  // ?? provides default value
  String result = nullableString ?? 'fallback';

  // ?. safe access
  String? name;
  int? length = name?.length; // null, no error
}
```

### Cascade Notation

```dart
void main() {
  var list = <int>[]
    ..add(1)
    ..add(2)
    ..add(3);
  print(list); // [1, 2, 3]
}
```

> **Key Point:** Use `~//` for integer division and `??` for providing default values to null expressions.

